Original Data Sources

We have a variety of data sources that our resource tracking data comes from. One of the primary sources that we have relied heavily on for data analysis is the FPM budgets.

The FPM budgets typically have a format like the image below:

An example of a FPM summary budget.

Some FPM budgets will also have tabs with even more detailed information. While the FPM budgets have very useful information about module and intervention activities per grant, SR information is not usually included in these budgets. To obtain SR information, we have found that PUDR documents can be very helpful for this.

An example of a PUDR with SR information.

So far, these are the two data sources from Uganda that we have for resource tracking data. We are actively seeking other sources of data to strengthen our analysis and understand how resources are disbursed.

The codebook for the database is also located in Basecamp, in the Resource Tracking folder. Here is what the current codebook looks like:

Contents of the codebook
Variable Class Possible Values Value Interpretation Notes
module character 64 unique values (e.g. TB/HIV) Global fund module that is allocated resources Can add more values if more documents become available
intervention integer 142 unique values (e.g. Facility Based Treament) Global fund intervention that is allocated resources Can add more values if more documents become available
sda_activity character 3553 unique values (e.g. procure test kits) Description of the activity that is allocated resources Can add more values if more documents become available
grant_number character 12 unique values (e.g. UGA-M-TASO) The grant associated with the RT data (e.g. UGA-M-MoFPED) NA
budget numeric minimum: 0 USD amount budgeted NA
expenditure character minimum: 0 USD expenditure amounts NA
disbursement character minimum: 0 USD amount disbursed NA
recipient character many Name of the grant recipient (either PR or SR) If no SR information, default to PR
start_date date any date value between 2005-01-01 to present date Start date corresponding to the rt data NA
period integer minimum: 0 Amount (in days) that correspond to the format of the grant (e.g. quarterly = 90,monthly" = 30) NA
disease character 4 unique values: hiv, hss, tb, malaria disease that corresponds to the grant NA
lang character 3 unique values: eng, fr, esp original language of the RT data can add more values if more languages appear
loc_name character 3 unique values: gtm, uga, cod ISO 3166-3 country code. A three-letter abbreviation of each country NA
data_source character 5 unique values: fpm, pudr, init_fpm, gos, sicoin Data source of the original RT data (e.g. pudr) Can add more values if more data sources become available
source character 2 unique values: gf, ghe Source of the RT data (e.g. gf = global fund, ghe = government health expenditures) NA
adm1 numeric 22 unique values (gtm), 4 unique (uga) or 26 (cod) First level subnational code corresponding to department (GTM), region (UGA), or province (DRC) If no subnational data, assign iso country code
adm2 numeric 435 (gtm), 111 unique values (uga), or 86 (cod) Second level subnational code corresponding to municipality (GTM) or district (UGA, DRC) If no subnational data, assign iso country code
cost_category character 58 unique values Global fund cost category that is allocated resources NA

It is possible that more variables will be added to the database as we continue to collect data. The codebook will be kept updated accordingly if this happens.

R Scripts for Data Prepping

The R scripts to prep the RT excel books are located in the github repository here: https://github.com/ihmeuw/gf/tree/develop/resource_tracking/prep/uga_prep

These are the scripts that you will need to prep the RT data and clean it into the same format as the RT database from the previous section.

These are the scripts that you will find in the uga_prep folder

At this point, you should have cloned the github repository to your local drive, but if you havent yet, this is a good guide for how to do so:

https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/setting-up-a-repository

Basecamp

In Basecamp, the RT data files are located here:

RT data files on Basecamp

You only need to download the fpm and pudrs folders onto your local drive - but make sure to save them in the same place (perhaps under the same folder name). If they are stored in different places on your local drive, you will need to modify the R code to accomodate this, since the R code assumes that both folders share a filepath.

The intervention_and_indicator_list Excel workbook is a file that contains all of the current GF modular framework interventions and indicators, as well as a tab that maps the old modules/interventions in past grants to the current framework. The module_mapping tab gets updated accordingly whenever we get new data that needs to be mapped to the framework. The main purpose of this is to standardize grant resources across country so that comparisons across grants can be as accurate as possible.

Running the Scripts

First, run the three individual prep scripts (detailed, summary, and pudr) before running the master prep file. In addition, you will need to run the map_modules_and_interventions.R script in the resource_tracking/prep/ repository folder. In the master prep file, there are a few parameters that need to be set. On line 31:

dir <- 'your local drive here' ##where the files are stored locally

You will need to enter the filepath of the RT documents.

You then should be able to run lines 32-100 without making any edits. Lines 99-100 are optional if you dont want to also output a summary file of the RT data.

At lines 164+ onwards, you will need to have run the map_modules_and_interventions.R prep script before continuing. This file can be found in: https://github.com/ihmeuw/gf/tree/develop/resource_tracking/prep/

Make sure to run all three functions inside this script or else the rest of the master_uga_prep script will not work.

Summary of Prep Scripts

The prep_detailed_budget file cleans the FPM budgets that have multiple levels of budget descriptors (i.e.service delivery area activities, sub-recipients, sub-national locations).

The prep_summary_budget file cleans the FPM budgets that only have module (and sometimes intervention) activities. When we can, we prefer to have detailed budgets over summary budgets in order toget the most granular level data.

The prep_pudr_uga file cleans the PUDR files we receive from the LFA. This script should flexible enough to handle PUDRs that are not all formatted the same, but may need to augmented if we receive a PUDR that has a different format.

The map_modules_and_interventions file maps the old modules and interventions to the current GF modular framework. It also accounts for differences in language (e.g.it maps the French version of a module to its GF English counterpart).
